# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: stateful-firewall
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] An **application-level gateway** (**ALG**, also known as **application-layer gateway**, **application gateway**, **application proxy**, or **application-level proxy**) is a security component that augments a firewall or NAT employed in a mobile network.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] It allows customized NAT traversal filters to be plugged into the gateway to support address and port translation for certain application layer "control/data" protocols such as FTP, BitTorrent, SIP, RTSP, file transfer in IM applications.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] In order for these protocols to work through NAT or a firewall, either the application has to know about an address/port number combination that allows incoming packets, or the NAT has to monitor the control traffic and open up port mappings (*firewall pinholes*) dynamically as required.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] Legitimate application data can thus be passed through the security checks of the firewall or NAT that would have otherwise restricted the traffic for not meeting its limited filter criteria.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] Deep packet inspection of all the packets handled by ALGs over a given network makes this functionality possible.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] An ALG understands the protocol used by the specific applications that it supports.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] For instance, for Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) Back-to-Back User agent (B2BUA), an ALG can allow firewall traversal with SIP.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] If the firewall has its SIP traffic terminated on an ALG then the responsibility for permitting SIP sessions passes to the ALG instead of the firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] An ALG can solve another major SIP headache: NAT traversal.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] Basically a NAT with a built-in ALG can rewrite information within the SIP messages and can hold address bindings until the session terminates.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] A SIP ALG will also handle SDP in the body of SIP messages (which is used ubiquitously in VoIP to set up media endpoints), since SDP also contains literal IP addresses and ports that must be translated.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] It is common for SIP ALG on some equipment to interfere with other technologies that try to solve the same problem, and various providers recommend turning it off.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] An ALG is very similar to a proxy server, as it sits between the client and real server, facilitating the exchange.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] There seems to be an industry convention that an ALG does its job without the application being configured to use it, by intercepting the messages.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] A proxy, on the other hand, usually needs to be configured in the client application.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] The client is then explicitly aware of the proxy and connects to it, rather than the real server.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] The *Application Layer Gateway* service in Microsoft Windows provides support for third-party plugins that allow network protocols to pass through the Windows Firewall and work behind it and Internet Connection Sharing.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] ALG plugins can open ports and change data that is embedded in packets, such as ports and IP addresses.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] Windows Server 2003 also includes an ALG FTP plugin.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] The ALG FTP plugin is designed to support active FTP sessions through the NAT engine in Windows.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] To do this, the ALG FTP plugin redirects all traffic that passes through the NAT and that is destined for port 21 (FTP control port) to a private listening port in the 3000–5000 range on the Microsoft *loopback adapter*.
[src:stateful-firewall/application-level-gateway] The ALG FTP plugin then monitors/updates traffic on the FTP control channel so that the FTP plugin can plumb port mappings through the NAT for the FTP data channels.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] An **Internet filter** is a type of Internet censorship that restricts or controls the content an Internet user is capable to access, especially when utilized to restrict material delivered over the Internet via the Web, Email, or other means.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The motive is often to prevent access to content which the computer's owner(s) or other authorities may consider objectionable.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] When imposed without the consent of the user, content control can be characterised as a form of internet censorship.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some filter software includes time control functions that empowers parents to set the amount of time that child may spend accessing the Internet or playing games or other computer activities.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The term "content control" is used on occasion by CNN, *Playboy* magazine, the *San Francisco Chronicle*, and *The New York Times*.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] However, several other terms, including "content filtering software", "web content filter", "filtering proxy servers", "secure web gateways", "censorware", "content security and control", "web filtering software", "content-censoring software", and "content-blocking software", are often used.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] "Nannyware" has also been used in both product marketing and by the media.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Industry research company Gartner uses **"secure web gateway"** (SWG) to describe the market segment.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some products log all sites that a user accesses and rates them based on content type for reporting to an "accountability partner" of the person's choosing, and the term accountability software is used.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Internet filters, parental control software, and/or accountability software may also be combined into one product.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Those critical of such software, however, use the term "censorware" freely: consider the Censorware Project, for example.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Filters can be implemented in many different ways: by software on a personal computer, via network infrastructure such as proxy servers, DNS servers, or firewalls that provide Internet access.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] No solution provides complete coverage, so most companies deploy a mix of technologies to achieve the proper content control in line with their policies.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] E-mail filters act on information contained in the mail body, in the mail headers such as sender and subject, and e-mail attachments to classify, accept, or reject messages.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] , a type of statistical filter, are commonly used.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Both client and server based filters are available.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] This type of filter is installed as software on each computer where filtering is required.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] This filter can typically be managed, disabled or uninstalled by anyone who has administrator-level privileges on the system.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Content-limited (or filtered) ISPs are Internet service providers that offer access to only a set portion of Internet content on an opt-in or a mandatory basis.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Anyone who subscribes to this type of service is subject to restrictions.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] functionality to filter outbound as well as inbound information.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] All users are subject to the access policy defined by the institution.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The filtering can be customized, so a school district's high school library can have a different filtering profile than the district's junior high school library.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] This type of filtering is implemented at the DNS layer and attempts to prevent lookups for domains that do not fit within a set of policies (either parental control or company rules).
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] offer filtering options as part of their services.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] can be also be used for this purpose, though client-side only.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] offer users the option of turning on a safety filter.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] When this safety filter is activated, it filters out the inappropriate links from all of the search results.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] If users know the actual URL of a website that features explicit or adult content, they have the ability to access that content without using a search engine.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some providers offer child-oriented versions of their engines that permit only child friendly websites.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some offer security software which includes parental controls.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] operating system also includes content-control software.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The Internet does not intrinsically provide content blocking, and therefore there is much content on the Internet that is considered unsuitable for children, given that much content is given certifications as suitable for adults only, e.g.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Internet service providers (ISPs) that block material containing pornography, or controversial religious, political, or news-related content en route are often utilized by parents who do not permit their children to access content not conforming to their personal beliefs.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Content filtering software can, however, also be used to block malware and other content that is or contains hostile, intrusive, or annoying material including adware, spam, computer viruses, worms, trojan horses, and spyware.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Most content control software is marketed to organizations or parents.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] It is, however, also marketed on occasion to facilitate self-censorship, for example by people struggling with addictions to online pornography, gambling, chat rooms, etc.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Self-censorship software may also be utilised by some in order to avoid viewing content they consider immoral, inappropriate, or simply distracting.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] A number of accountability software products are marketed as *self-censorship* or *accountability software*.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] These are often promoted by religious media and at religious gatherings.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Content filtering technology exists in two major forms: application gateway or packet inspection.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] For HTTP access the application gateway is called a web-proxy or just a proxy.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Such web-proxies can inspect both the initial request and the returned web page using arbitrarily complex rules and will not return any part of the page to the requester until a decision is made.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In addition they can make substitutions in whole or for any part of the returned result.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Packet inspection filters do not initially interfere with the connection to the server but inspect the data in the connection as it goes past, at some point the filter may decide that the connection is to be filtered and it will then disconnect it by injecting a TCP-Reset or similar faked packet.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The two techniques can be used together with the packet filter monitoring a link until it sees an HTTP connection starting to an IP address that has content that needs filtering.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The packet filter then redirects the connection to the web-proxy which can perform detailed filtering on the website without having to pass through all unfiltered connections.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] This combination is quite popular because it can significantly reduce the cost of the system.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] There are constraints to IP level packet-filtering, as it may result in rendering all web content associated with a particular IP address inaccessible.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] This may result in the unintentional blocking of legitimate sites that share the same IP address or domain.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] For instance, university websites commonly employ multiple domains under one IP address.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Moreover, IP level packet-filtering can be surpassed by using a distinct IP address for certain content while still being linked to the same domain or server.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Gateway-based content control software may be more difficult to bypass than desktop software as the user does not have physical access to the filtering device.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] However, many of the techniques in the Bypassing filters section still work.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Content labeling may be considered another form of content-control software.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In 1994, the Internet Content Rating Association (ICRA) — now part of the Family Online Safety Institute — developed a content rating system for online content providers.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Using an online questionnaire a webmaster describes the nature of their web content.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] A small file is generated that contains a condensed, computer readable digest of this description that can then be used by content filtering software to block or allow that site.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] ICRA labels come in a variety of formats.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] These include the World Wide Web Consortium's Resource Description Framework (RDF) as well as Platform for Internet Content Selection (PICS) labels used by Microsoft's Internet Explorer Content Advisor.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] ICRA labels are an example of self-labeling.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Similarly, in 2006 the Association of Sites Advocating Child Protection (ASACP) initiated the Restricted to Adults self-labeling initiative.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] ASACP members were concerned that various forms of legislation being proposed in the United States were going to have the effect of forcing adult companies to label their content.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The RTA label, unlike ICRA labels, does not require a webmaster to fill out a questionnaire or sign up to use.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Both labels are recognized by a wide variety of content-control software.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The Voluntary Content Rating (VCR) system was devised by Solid Oak Software for their CYBERsitter filtering software, as an alternative to the PICS system, which some critics deemed too complex.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] It employs HTML metadata tags embedded within web page documents to specify the type of content contained in the document.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Only two levels are specified, *mature* and *adult*, making the specification extremely simple.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The Australian Internet Safety Advisory Body has information about "practical advice on Internet safety, parental control and filters for the protection of children, students and families" that also includes public libraries.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] NetAlert, the software made available free of charge by the Australian government, was allegedly cracked by a 16-year-old student, Tom Wood, less than a week after its release in August 2007.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Wood supposedly bypassed the $84 million filter in about half an hour to highlight problems with the government's approach to Internet content filtering.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The Australian Government has introduced legislation that requires ISPs to "restrict access to age restricted content (commercial MA15+ content and R18+ content) either hosted in Australia or provided from Australia" that was due to commence from 20 January 2008, known as Cleanfeed.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a proposed mandatory ISP level content filtration system.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] It was proposed by the Beazley led Australian Labor Party opposition in a 2006 press release, with the intention of protecting children who were vulnerable due to claimed parental computer illiteracy.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] It was announced on 31 December 2007 as a policy to be implemented by the Rudd ALP government, and initial tests in Tasmania have produced a 2008 report.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is funded in the current budget, and is moving towards an Expression of Interest for live testing with ISPs in 2008.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Public opposition and criticism have emerged, led by the EFA and gaining irregular mainstream media attention, with a majority of Australians reportedly "strongly against" its implementation.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Criticisms include its expense, inaccuracy (it will be impossible to ensure only illegal sites are blocked) and the fact that it will be compulsory, which can be seen as an intrusion on free speech rights.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Another major criticism point has been that although the filter is claimed to stop certain materials, the underground rings dealing in such materials will not be affected.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The filter might also provide a false sense of security for parents, who might supervise children less while using the Internet, achieving the exact opposite effect.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Cleanfeed is a responsibility of Senator Conroy's portfolio.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In Denmark it is stated policy that it will "prevent inappropriate Internet sites from being accessed from children's libraries across Denmark".
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] "'It is important that every library in the country has the opportunity to protect children against pornographic material when they are using library computers.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Many libraries in the UK such as the British Library and local authority public libraries apply filters to Internet access.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] According to research conducted by the Radical Librarians Collective, at least 98% of public libraries apply filters; including categories such as "LGBT interest", "abortion" and "questionable".
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The use of Internet filters or content-control software varies widely in public libraries in the United States, since Internet use policies are established by the local library board.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Many libraries adopted Internet filters after Congress conditioned the receipt of universal service discounts on the use of Internet filters through the Children's Internet Protection Act (CIPA).
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Other libraries do not install content control software, believing that acceptable use policies and educational efforts address the issue of children accessing age-inappropriate content while preserving adult users' right to freely access information.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some libraries use Internet filters on computers used by children only.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Many legal scholars believe that a number of legal cases, in particular *Reno v.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] American Civil Liberties Union*, established that the use of content-control software in libraries is a violation of the First Amendment.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The Children's Internet Protection Act [CIPA] and the June 2003 case *United States v.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The plurality decision left open a future "as-applied" Constitutional challenge, however.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In November 2006, a lawsuit was filed against the North Central Regional Library District (NCRL) in Washington State for its policy of refusing to disable restrictions upon requests of adult patrons, but CIPA was not challenged in that matter.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The Court said: "It appears to us that NCRL's filtering policy is reasonable and accords with its mission and these policies and is viewpoint neutral.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] It appears that no article I, section 5 content-based violation exists in this case.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] NCRL's essential mission is to promote reading and lifelong learning.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] As NCRL maintains, it is reasonable to impose restrictions on Internet access in order to maintain an environment that is conducive to study and contemplative thought." The case returned to federal court.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In March 2007, Virginia passed a law similar to CIPA that requires public libraries receiving state funds to use content-control software.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Like CIPA, the law requires libraries to disable filters for an adult library user when requested to do so by the user.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Utilizing a filter that is overly zealous at filtering content, or mislabels content not intended to be censored can result in over-blocking, or over-censoring.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Overblocking can filter out material that should be acceptable under the filtering policy in effect, for example health related information may unintentionally be filtered along with porn-related material because of the Scunthorpe problem.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Filter administrators may prefer to err on the side of caution by accepting over blocking to prevent any risk of access to sites that they determine to be undesirable.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Content-control software was mentioned as blocking access to Beaver College before its name change to Arcadia University.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Another example was the filtering of Horniman Museum.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] As well, over-blocking may encourage users to bypass the filter entirely.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Whenever new information is uploaded to the Internet, filters can under block, or under-censor, content if the parties responsible for maintaining the filters do not update them quickly and accurately, and a blacklisting rather than a whitelisting filtering policy is in place.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Many would not be satisfied with government filtering viewpoints on moral or political issues, agreeing that this could become support for propaganda.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Many would also find it unacceptable that an ISP, whether by law or by the ISP's own choice, should deploy such software without allowing the users to disable the filtering for their own connections.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In the United States, the First Amendment to the United States Constitution has been cited in calls to criminalise forced internet censorship.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Many types of content-control software have been shown to block sites based on the religious and political leanings of the company owners.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Examples include blocking several religious sites (including the Web site of the Vatican), many political sites, and homosexuality-related sites.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] *X-Stop* was shown to block sites such as the Quaker web site, the National Journal of Sexual Orientation Law, The Heritage Foundation, and parts of The Ethical Spectacle.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] CYBERsitter blocks out sites like National Organization for Women.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Nancy Willard, an academic researcher and attorney, pointed out that many U.S. public schools and libraries use the same filtering software that many Christian organizations use.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In 1998, a United States federal district court in Virginia ruled (Loudoun v.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Board of Trustees of the Loudoun County Library) that the imposition of mandatory filtering in a public library violates the First Amendment.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In 1996 the US Congress passed the Communications Decency Act, banning indecency on the Internet.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Civil liberties groups challenged the law under the First Amendment, and in 1997 the Supreme Court ruled in their favor.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Part of the civil liberties argument, especially from groups like the Electronic Frontier Foundation, was that parents who wanted to block sites could use their own content-filtering software, making government involvement unnecessary.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] In the late 1990s, groups such as the Censorware Project began reverse-engineering the content-control software and decrypting the blacklists to determine what kind of sites the software blocked.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] This led to legal action alleging violation of the "Cyber Patrol" license agreement.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] They discovered that such tools routinely blocked unobjectionable sites while also failing to block intended targets.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some content-control software companies responded by claiming that their filtering criteria were backed by intensive manual checking.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The companies' opponents argued, on the other hand, that performing the necessary checking would require resources greater than the companies possessed and that therefore their claims were not valid.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] The Motion Picture Association successfully obtained a UK ruling enforcing ISPs to use content-control software to prevent copyright infringement by their subscribers.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Content filtering in general can "be bypassed entirely by tech-savvy individuals." Blocking content on a device "[will not]…guarantee that users won't eventually be able to find a way around the filter." Content providers may change URLs or IP addresses to circumvent filtering.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Individuals with technical expertise may use a different method by employing multiple domains or URLs that direct to a shared IP address where restricted content is present.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] This strategy doesn't circumvent IP packet filtering, however can evade DNS poisoning and web proxies.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Additionally, perpetrators may use mirrored websites that avoid filters.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some software may be bypassed successfully by using alternative protocols such as FTP or telnet or HTTPS, conducting searches in a different language, using a proxy server or a circumventor such as Psiphon.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Also cached web pages returned by Google or other searches could bypass some controls as well.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Web syndication services may provide alternate paths for content.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Some of the more poorly designed programs can be shut down by killing their processes: for example, in Microsoft Windows through the Windows Task Manager, or in Mac OS X using Force Quit or Activity Monitor.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Numerous workarounds and counters to workarounds from content-control software creators exist.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Google services are often blocked by filters, but these may most often be bypassed by using *https://* in place of *http://* since content filtering software is not able to interpret content under secure connections (in this case SSL).
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] An encrypted VPN can be used as means of bypassing content control software, especially if the content control software is installed on an Internet gateway or firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/content-control-software] Other ways to bypass a content control filter include translation sites and establishing a remote connection with an uncensored device.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] There are multiple ways to acquire packets for deep packet inspection.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Using port mirroring (sometimes called Span Port) is a very common way, as well as physically inserting a network tap which duplicates and sends the data stream to an analyzer tool for inspection.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection (and filtering) enables advanced network management, user service, and security functions as well as Internet data mining, eavesdropping, and censorship.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Although DPI has been used for Internet management for many years, some advocates of net neutrality fear that the technique may be used anticompetitively or to reduce the openness of the Internet.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI is used in a wide range of applications, at the “enterprise level” (according to corporations and larger institutions), telecommunications service providers, and governments.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI technology has a long and technologically advanced history, starting in the 1990s, before the technology entered what is seen today as common, mainstream deployments.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Essential DPI functionality includes analysis of packet headers and protocol fields.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] For example, Wireshark offers essential DPI functionality through its numerous dissectors that display field names and content and, in some cases, offer interpretation of field values.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Some security solutions that offer DPI combine the functionality of an intrusion detection system (IDS) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS) with a traditional stateful firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] This combination makes it possible to detect certain attacks that neither the IDS/IPS nor the stateful firewall can catch on their own.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Stateful firewalls, while able to see the beginning and end of a packet flow, cannot catch events on their own that would be out of bounds for a particular application.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] While IDSs are able to detect intrusions, they have very little capability in blocking such an attack.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPIs are used to prevent attacks from viruses and worms at wire speeds.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] More specifically, DPI can be effective against buffer overflow attacks, denial-of-service attacks (DoS), sophisticated intrusions, and a small percentage of worms that fit within a single packet.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI-enabled devices have the ability to look at Layer 2 and beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In some cases, DPI can be invoked to look through Layer 2-7 of the OSI model.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] This includes headers and data protocol structures as well as the payload of the message.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI functionality is invoked when a device looks or takes other action based on information beyond Layer 3 of the OSI model.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI can identify and classify traffic based on a signature database that includes information extracted from the data part of a packet, allowing finer control than classification based only on header information.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] End points can utilize encryption and obfuscation techniques to evade DPI actions in many cases.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] A classified packet may be redirected, marked/tagged (see quality of service), blocked, rate limited, and of course, reported to a reporting agent in the network.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In this way, HTTP errors of different classifications may be identified and forwarded for analysis.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Many DPI devices can identify packet flows (rather than packet-by-packet analysis), allowing control actions based on accumulated flow information.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Initially security at the enterprise level was just a perimeter discipline, with a dominant philosophy of keeping unauthorized users out, and shielding authorized users from the outside world.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The most frequently used tool for accomplishing this has been a stateful firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] It can permit fine-grained control of access from the outside world to pre-defined destinations on the internal network, as well as permitting access back to other hosts only if a request to the outside world has been made previously.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Vulnerabilities exist at network layers, however, that are not visible to a stateful firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Firewalls also do not distinguish between permitted and forbidden uses of legitimately-accessed applications.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI enables IT administrators and security officials to set policies and enforce them at all layers, including the application and user layer to help combat those threats.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is able to detect a few kinds of buffer overflow attacks.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI may be used by enterprise for Data Leak Prevention (DLP).
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] When an e-mail user tries to send a protected file, the user may be given information on how to get the proper clearance to send the file.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI to secure their internal networks, Internet service providers (ISPs) also apply it on the public networks provided to customers.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Common uses of DPI by ISPs are lawful intercept, policy definition and enforcement, targeted advertising, quality of service, offering tiered services, and copyright enforcement.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers are required by almost all governments worldwide to enable lawful intercept capabilities.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Decades ago in a legacy telephone environment, this was met by creating a traffic access point (TAP) using an intercepting proxy server that connects to the government's surveillance equipment.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The acquisition component of this functionality may be provided in many ways, including DPI, DPI-enabled products that are "LI or CALEA-compliant" can be used – when directed by a court order – to access a user's datastream.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In some countries the ISPs are required to perform filtering, depending on the country's laws.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows service providers to "readily know the packets of information you are receiving online—from e-mail, to websites, to sharing of music, video and software downloads".
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Because ISPs route the traffic of all of their customers, they are able to monitor web-browsing habits in a very detailed way allowing them to gain information about their customers' interests, which can be used by companies specializing in targeted advertising.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] At least 100,000 United States customers are tracked this way, and as many as 10% of U.S. customers have been tracked in this way.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Technology providers include NebuAd, Front Porch, and Phorm.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs monitoring their customers include Knology and Wide Open West.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In addition, the United Kingdom ISP British Telecom has admitted testing solutions from Phorm without their customers' knowledge or consent.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Applications such as peer-to-peer (P2P) traffic present increasing problems for broadband service providers.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Typically, P2P traffic is used by applications that do file sharing.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] These may be any kind of files (i.e. documents, music, videos, or applications).
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Due to the frequently large size of media files being transferred, P2P drives increasing traffic loads, requiring additional network capacity.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Service providers say a minority of users generate large quantities of P2P traffic and degrade performance for the majority of broadband subscribers using applications such as e-mail or Web browsing which use less bandwidth.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Poor network performance increases customer dissatisfaction and leads to a decline in service revenues.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI allows the operators to oversell their available bandwidth while ensuring equitable bandwidth distribution to all users by preventing network congestion.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Additionally, a higher priority can be allocated to a VoIP or video conferencing call which requires low latency versus web browsing which does not.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] This is the approach that service providers use to dynamically allocate bandwidth according to traffic that is passing through their networks.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Mobile and broadband service providers use DPI as a means to implement tiered service plans, to differentiate "walled garden" services from "value added", "all-you-can-eat" and "one-size-fits-all" data services.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] ISPs are sometimes requested by copyright owners or required by courts or official policy to help enforce copyrights.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, one of Denmark's largest ISPs, Tele2, was given a court injunction and told it must block its customers from accessing The Pirate Bay, a launching point for BitTorrent.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Instead of prosecuting file sharers one at a time, the International Federation of the Phonographic Industry (IFPI) and the big four record labels EMI, Sony BMG, Universal Music, and Warner Music have sued ISPs such as Eircom for not doing enough about protecting their copyrights.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA), which aims to enforce movie copyrights, has taken the position with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) that network neutrality could hurt anti-piracy techniques such as deep packet inspection and other forms of filtering.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In addition to using DPI for the security of their own networks, governments in North America, Europe, and Asia use DPI for various purposes such as surveillance and censorship.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The Chinese government uses deep packet inspection to monitor and censor network traffic and content that it claims is harmful to Chinese citizens or state interests.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] This material includes pornography, information on religion, and political dissent.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Chinese network ISPs use DPI to see if there is any sensitive keyword going through their network.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] China previously blocked all VoIP traffic in and out of their country but many available VoIP applications now function in China.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Voice traffic in Skype is unaffected, although text messages are subject to filtering, and messages containing sensitive material, such as curse-words, are simply not delivered, with no notification provided to either participant in the conversation.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] China also blocks visual media sites such as YouTube.com and various photography and blogging sites.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Since 2015, Egypt reportedly started to join the list which was constantly being denied by the Egyptian National Telecom Regulatory Authority (NTRA) officials.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] However, it came to news when the country decided to block the encrypted messaging app Signal as announced by the application's developer.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In April 2017, all VoIP applications including FaceTime, Facebook Messenger, Viber, WhatsApp calls and Skype have been all blocked in the country.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] As of 2022, FaceTime, Facebook Messenger are unblocked.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The Indian ISP Jio, which is also the largest network operator in India has been known to employ sophisticated DPI techniques like SNI-based filtering to enforce censorship.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The Indonesian government via Telkom Indonesia, supported by Cisco Meraki DPI technology, perform country-wide surveillance by the way of deep packet inspection, and map it into SSN/NIK (Nomor Induk Kependudukan) of its citizens that registered to the state-owned ISP.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of deep packet inspection including filtering porn, hate speech, and reducing tension in West Papua.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Indonesian Government planned to scale up the surveillance to next level until 2030.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] According to unnamed experts cited in the article, the system "enables authorities to not only block communication but to monitor it to gather information about individuals, as well as alter it for disinformation purposes".
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The system was purchased by the Telecommunication Infrastructure Co., part of the Iranian government's telecom monopoly.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] According to the *Journal*, NSN "provided equipment to Iran last year under the internationally recognized concept of 'lawful intercept,' said Mr.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] That relates to intercepting data for the purposes of combating terrorism, child pornography, drug trafficking, and other criminal activities carried out online, a capability that most if not all telecom companies have, he said....
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] He said the company determined it was no longer part of its core business.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The NSN system followed on purchases by Iran from Secure Computing Corp. earlier in the decade.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Questions have been raised about the reporting reliability of the *Journal* report by David Isenberg, an independent Washington, D.C.–based analyst and Cato Institute Adjunct Scholar, specifically saying that Mr.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Roome is denying the quotes attributed to him and that he, Isenberg, also had similar complaints with one of the same *Journal* reporters in an earlier story.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] NSN has issued the following denial: NSN "has not provided any deep packet inspection, web censorship or Internet filtering capability to Iran".
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] A concurrent article in *The New York Times* stated the NSN sale had been covered in a "spate of news reports in April [2009], including *The Washington Times*," and reviewed censorship of the Internet and other media in the country, but did not mention DPI.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] According to Walid Al-Saqaf, the developer of the internet censorship circumventor Alkasir, Iran was using deep packet inspection in February 2012, bringing internet speeds in the entire country to a near standstill.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] This briefly eliminated access to tools such as Tor and Alkasir.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The incumbent Malaysian government, headed by Barisan Nasional, was said to be using DPI against a political opponent during the run-up to the 13th general elections held on 5 May 2013.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The purpose of DPI, in this instance, was to block and/or hinder access to selected websites, e.g.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Facebook accounts, blogs and news portals.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The Pakistan Telecommunication Authority (PTA) states that the DPI system has been installed to implement the Prevention of Electronic Crimes Act (PECA) 2016, particularly to filter and block blasphemous content and any material that is considered to be against the integrity or security of Pakistan.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Canadian firm Sandvine was contracted to provide and set up the equipment in Pakistan.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Federal Law No.139 enforces blocking websites on the Russian Internet blacklist using IP filtering, but does not force ISPs into analyzing the data part of packets.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Yet some ISPs still use different DPI solutions to implement blacklisting.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] For 2019, the governmental agency Roskomnadzor is planning a nationwide rollout of DPI after the pilot project in one of the country's regions, at an estimated cost of 20 billion roubles (US$300M).
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The city state reportedly employs deep packet inspection of Internet traffic.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] FCC adopts Internet CALEA requirements: The FCC, pursuant to its mandate from the U.S.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Congress, and in line with the policies of most countries worldwide, has required that all telecommunication providers, including Internet services, be capable of supporting the execution of a court order to provide real-time communication forensics of specified users.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] In 2006, the FCC adopted new Title 47, Subpart Z, rules requiring Internet Access Providers to meet these requirements.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] DPI was one of the platforms essential to meeting this requirement and has been deployed for this purpose throughout the U.S.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The National Security Agency (NSA), with cooperation from AT&T Inc., has used deep packet inspection to make internet traffic surveillance, sorting, and forwarding more intelligent.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The DPI is used to find which packets are carrying e-mail or a Voice over Internet Protocol (VoIP) telephone call.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Traffic associated with AT&T's Common Backbone was "split" between two fibers, dividing the signal so that 50 percent of the signal strength went to each output fiber.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] One of the output fibers was diverted to a secure room; the other carried communications on to AT&T's switching equipment.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The secure room contained Narus traffic analyzers and logic servers; Narus states that such devices are capable of real-time data collection (recording data for consideration) and capture at 10 gigabits per second.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Certain traffic was selected and sent over a dedicated line to a "central location" for analysis.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] According to an affidavit by expert witness J.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Narus's Semantic Traffic Analyzer software, which runs on IBM or Dell Linux servers using DPI, sorts through IP traffic at 10 Gbit/s to pick out specific messages based on a targeted e-mail address, IP address or, in the case of VoIP, telephone number.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Gonzales have asserted that they believe the president has the authority to order secret intercepts of telephone and e-mail exchanges between people inside the United States and their contacts abroad without obtaining a FISA warrant.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] The Defense Information Systems Agency has developed a sensor platform that uses deep packet inspection.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Vietnam launched its network security center and required ISPs to upgrade their hardware systems to use deep packet inspection to block Internet traffic.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Deep packet inspection is considered by many to undermine the infrastructure of the internet.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] There is a greater emphasis being placed on deep packet inspection - this comes in light after the rejection of both the SOPA and PIPA bills.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Many current DPI methods are slow and costly, especially for high bandwidth applications.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] More efficient methods of DPI are being developed.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Specialized routers are now able to perform DPI; routers armed with a dictionary of programs will help identify the purposes behind the LAN and internet traffic they are routing.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] Cisco Systems is now on their second iteration of DPI enabled routers, with their announcement of the CISCO ISR G2 router.
[src:stateful-firewall/deep-packet-inspection] A comprehensive comparison of various network traffic classifiers, which depend on deep packet inspection (PACE, OpenDPI, 4 different configurations of L7-filter, NDPI, Libprotoident, and Cisco NBAR), is shown in the Independent Comparison of Popular DPI Tools for Traffic Classification.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] In computing, a **firewall** is a network security system that monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on configurable security rules.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] A firewall typically establishes a barrier between a trusted network and an untrusted network, such as the Internet or between several VLANs.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Firewalls can be categorized as network-based or host-based.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The term *firewall* originally referred to a wall to confine a fire within a line of adjacent buildings.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Later uses refer to similar structures, such as the metal sheet separating the engine compartment of a vehicle or aircraft from the passenger compartment.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The term was applied in the 1980s to network technology that emerged when the Internet was fairly new in terms of its global use and connectivity.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The predecessors to firewalls for network security were routers used in the 1980s.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Because they already segregated networks, routers could filter packets crossing them.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Before it was used in real-life computing, the term appeared in John Badham's 1983 computer‑hacking movie *WarGames*, spoken by the bearded and bespectacled programmer named Paul Richter, which possibly inspired its later use.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] One of the earliest commercially successful firewall and network address translation (NAT) products was the PIX (Private Internet eXchange) Firewall, invented in 1994 by Network Translation Inc., a startup founded and run by John Mayes.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The PIX Firewall technology was coded by Brantley Coile as a consultant software developer.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Recognizing the emerging IPv4 address depletion problem, they designed the PIX to enable organizations to securely connect private networks to the public internet using a limited number of registered IP addresses.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The innovative PIX solution quickly gained industry acclaim, earning the prestigious "Hot Product of the Year" award from Data Communications Magazine in January 1995.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Cisco Systems, seeking to expand into the rapidly growing network security market, subsequently acquired Network Translation Inc. in November 1995 to obtain the rights to the PIX technology.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The PIX became one of Cisco's flagship firewall product lines before eventually being succeeded by the Adaptive Security Appliance (ASA) platform introduced in 2005.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Firewalls are categorized as a network-based or a host-based system.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Network-based firewalls are positioned between two or more networks, typically between the local area network (LAN) and wide area network (WAN), their basic function being to control the flow of data between connected networks.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] They are either a software appliance running on general-purpose hardware, a hardware appliance running on special-purpose hardware, or a virtual appliance running on a virtual host controlled by a hypervisor.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Firewall appliances may also offer non-firewall functionality, such as DHCP or VPN services.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Host-based firewalls are deployed directly on the host itself to control network traffic or other computing resources.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] This can be a daemon or service as a part of the operating system or an agent application for protection.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The first reported type of network firewall is called a packet filter which inspects packets transferred between computers.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The firewall maintains an access-control list which dictates what packets will be looked at and what action should be applied, if any, with the default action set to silent discard.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Three basic actions regarding the packet consist of a silent discard, discard with Internet Control Message Protocol or TCP reset response to the sender, and forward to the next hop.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Packets may be filtered by source and destination IP addresses, protocol, or source and destination ports.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The first paper published on firewall technology was in 1987 when engineers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC) developed filter systems known as packet filter firewalls.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] At AT&T Bell Labs, Bill Cheswick and Steve Bellovin continued their research in packet filtering and developed a working model for their own company based on their original first-generation architecture.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] In 1992, Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson released a paper on BSD Packet Filter (BPF) while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] From 1989 to 1990, three colleagues from AT&T Bell Laboratories, Dave Presotto, Janardan Sharma, and Kshitij Nigam, developed the second generation of firewalls, calling them circuit-level gateways.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Marcus Ranum, Wei Xu, and Peter Churchyard released an application firewall known as Firewall Toolkit (FWTK) in October 1993.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] This became the basis for Gauntlet firewall at Trusted Information Systems.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The key benefit of application layer filtering is that it can understand certain applications and protocols such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP), Domain Name System (DNS), or Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] This allows it to identify unwanted applications or services using a non standard port, or detect if an allowed protocol is being abused.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] It can also provide unified security management including enforced encrypted DNS and virtual private networking.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Endpoint-based application firewalls function by determining whether a process should accept any given connection.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Application firewalls filter connections by examining the process ID of data packets against a rule set for the local process involved in the data transmission.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Application firewalls accomplish their function by hooking into socket calls to filter the connections between the application layer and the lower layers.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Application firewalls that hook into socket calls are also referred to as socket filters.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] At the core of a firewall's operation are the policies that govern its decision-making process.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] These policies, collectively known as firewall rules, are the specific guidelines that determine the traffic allowed or blocked across a network's boundaries.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Firewall rules are based on the evaluation of network packets against predetermined security criteria.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] A network packet, which carries data across networks, must match certain attributes defined in a rule to be allowed through the firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Zones are logical segments within a network that group together devices with similar security requirements.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] By partitioning a network into zones, such as "Technical", "WAN", "LAN", "Public," "Private," "DMZ", and "Wireless," administrators can enforce policies that control the flow of traffic between them.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Each zone has its own level of trust and is governed by specific firewall rules that regulate the ingress and egress of data.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] A typical default is to allow all traffic from LAN to WAN, and to drop all traffic from WAN to LAN.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] In networking terms, services are specific functions typically identified by a network port and protocol.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Common examples include HTTP/HTTPS (web traffic) on ports 80 and 443, FTP (file transfer) on port 21, and SMTP (email) on port 25.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Services are the engines behind the applications users depend on.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] From a security aspect, controlling access to services is crucial because services are common targets for exploitation.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Firewalls employ rules that stipulate which services should be accessible, to whom, and in what context.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] For example, a firewall might be configured to block incoming FTP requests to prevent unauthorized file uploads but allow outgoing HTTPS requests for web browsing.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Applications refer to the software systems that users interact with while on the network.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] They can range from web browsers and email clients to complex database systems and cloud-based services.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] In network security, applications are important because different types of traffic can pose varying security risks.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Thus, firewall rules can be crafted to identify and control traffic based on the application generating or receiving it.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] By using application awareness, firewalls can allow, deny, or limit traffic for specific applications according to organizational policies and compliance requirements, thereby mitigating potential threats from vulnerable or undesired applications.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Application can both be a grouping of services, or a L7 inspection.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Implementing firewall rules based on IP addresses alone is often insufficient due to the dynamic nature of user location and device usage.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] User ID will be translated to an IP address.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] This is where the concept of "User ID" makes a significant impact.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] User ID allows firewall rules to be crafted based on individual user identities, rather than just fixed source or destination IP addresses.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] This enhances security by enabling more granular control over who can access certain network resources, regardless of where they are connecting from or what device they are using.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] The User ID technology is typically integrated into firewall systems through the use of directory services such as Active Directory, LDAP, RADIUS or TACACS+.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] These services link the user's login information to their network activities.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] By doing this, the firewall can apply rules and policies that correspond to user groups, roles, or individual user accounts instead of purely relying on the network topology.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Consider a school that wants to restrict access to a social media server from students.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] They can create a rule in the firewall that utilises User ID information to enforce this policy.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] User Identification — The firewall maps network traffic to specific user IDs by interpreting authentication logs.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] When a user logs on, the firewall associates that login with the user's IP address.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Define User Groups — Within the firewall's management interface, define user groups based on the directory service.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] For example, create groups such as "Students".
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] With this setup, only users who authenticate and are identified as members of "Students" are denied to access social media servers.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] All other traffic, starting from LAN interfaces, will be allowed.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Setting up a firewall is a complex and error-prone task.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] A network may face security issues due to configuration errors.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Firewall policies are typically configured according to the type of network in use, such as public or private environments.
[src:stateful-firewall/firewall-computing] Administrators define rules that permit or restrict traffic in order to reduce exposure to threats like unauthorized access, malware, or other forms of cyberattack.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] A **next-generation firewall** (**NGFW**) is a part of the third generation of firewall technology, combining a conventional firewall with other network device filtering functions, such as an application firewall using in-line deep packet inspection (DPI) and an intrusion prevention system (IPS).
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Other techniques might also be employed, such as TLS-encrypted traffic inspection, website filtering, QoS/bandwidth management, antivirus inspection, third-party identity management integration (e.g.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] LDAP, RADIUS, Active Directory), and SSL decryption.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] **Unified Threat Management** refers to a similar appliance as an NGFW.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] One of the first mentions of the NGFW term was in a 2004 document by Gartner.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Kenneth Tam speculated that the term Unified Threat Management (UTM) was coined by IDC because they did not want to adopt the name of their competitor.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] NGFWs include the typical functions of traditional firewalls such as packet filtering, network- and port-address translation (NAT), stateful inspection, and virtual private network (VPN) support.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] The goal of next-generation firewalls is to include more layers of the OSI model, improving filtering of network traffic that is dependent on the packet contents.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] The most significant differences are that NGFWs include intrusion prevention systems (IPS) and application control.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Next-generation firewalls perform deeper inspection compared to stateful inspection performed by the first- and second-generation firewalls.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] NGFWs use a more thorough inspection style, checking packet payloads and matching signatures for harmful activities such as exploitable attacks and malware.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Modern threats like web-based malware attacks, targeted attacks, application-layer attacks, and more have had a significantly negative effect on the threat landscape.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] In fact, one in four attacks exploit vulnerabilities in public-facing applications, as opposed to weaknesses in networking components and services.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Stateful firewalls with simple packet filtering capabilities were efficient blocking unwanted applications as most applications met the port-protocol expectations.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Administrators could promptly prevent an unsafe application from being accessed by users by blocking the associated ports and protocols.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] But blocking a web application that uses port 80 by closing the port would also mean complications with the entire HTTP protocol.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Protection based on ports, protocols, IP addresses is no more reliable and viable.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] This has led to the development of identity-based security approach, which takes organizations a step ahead of conventional security appliances which bind security to IP-addresses.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] NGFWs offer administrators a deeper awareness of and control over individual applications, along with deeper inspection capabilities by the firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/next-generation-firewall] Administrators can create very granular "allow/deny" rules for controlling use of websites and applications in the network.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] In computing, a **stateful firewall** is a network-based firewall that individually tracks sessions of network connections traversing it.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] **Stateful packet inspection**, also referred to as dynamic packet filtering, is a security feature often used in non-commercial and business networks.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] A stateful firewall keeps track of the state of network connections, such as TCP streams, UDP datagrams, and ICMP messages, and can apply labels such as *LISTEN*, *ESTABLISHED*, or *CLOSING*.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] State table entries are created for TCP streams or UDP datagrams that are allowed to communicate through the firewall in accordance with the configured security policy.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] Once in the table, all *RELATED* packets of a stored session are streamlined, taking fewer CPU cycles than standard inspection.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] Related packets are also permitted to return through the firewall even if no rule is configured to allow communications from that host.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] If no traffic is seen for a specified time (time-out implementation dependent), the connection is removed from the state table.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] This can lead to applications experiencing unexpected disconnects or half-open TCP connections.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] Applications can be written to send keepalive messages periodically to prevent a firewall from dropping the connection during periods of no activity or for applications which by design have long periods of silence.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] The method of maintaining a session's state depends on the transport protocol being used.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] TCP is a connection-oriented protocol and sessions are established with a three-way handshake using *SYN* packets and ended by sending a *FIN* notification.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] The firewall can use these unique connection identifiers to know when to remove a session from the state table without waiting for a timeout.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] UDP is a connectionless protocol, which means it does not send unique connection-related identifiers while communicating.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] Because of that, a session will only be removed from the state table after the configured time-out.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] UDP hole punching is a technology that leverages this trait to allow for dynamically setting up data tunnels over the internet.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] ICMP messages are distinct from TCP and UDP and communicate control information of the network itself.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] A well-known example of this is the ping utility.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] ICMP responses will be allowed back through the firewall.
[src:stateful-firewall/stateful-firewall] In some scenarios, UDP communication can use ICMP to provide information about the state of the session so ICMP responses related to a UDP session will also be allowed back through.
